<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-803-646  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 803 646.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 27 1990 v4 n31 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DOD reins in non-essential spending; services told to redirectfunds to Saudi Arabia operations. (the US Department of Defense'sOperation Desert Shield)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Department of Defense (DOD) cut non-essential spending tohelp pay for Operation Desert Shield in Saudi Arabia, beginning byordering individual services to conserve tight operations andmaintenance (Oandamp;M) funds.andP;  The DOD will likely spend little onpurely administrative data processing systems in the 4th qtr ofthe current fiscal year, which is usually the highest spendingperiod.andP;  DOD Comptroller Sean O'Keefe sent a message to allservices telling them to investigate options to cut Oandamp;M; the Armyresponded by telling all its commands to stop all non-essential,non-discretionary operations for the rest of FY 1990 and toredirect the funds to Desert Shield.andP;  All Air Force commands weretold to limit remaining FY 1990 Oandamp;M expenditures tomission-essential, readiness-related requirements, and an industrysource says the Marines froze all FY 1990 funding as soon as thefirst Marine left for Saudi Arabia; the Navy is expected to followsuit, although its plans were not detailed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MilitaryGovernment AgencyGovernment FundingBudgetingPlanningEquipment AcquisitionEDP BudgetingUnited States. Department of DefenseOperation Desert Shield.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>